16 successor.
17 (f) If the developer agrees to guarantee the level of assessments for the timeshare
18 program for any period of time, the developer may be excused from the payment of the
19 developer's share of the assessments that otherwise would have been assessed against
20 developer-owned timeshares during the guarantee period, provided that the developer guarantees
21 that (i) during the guarantee period the assessments against owner timeshares will not increase
22 over the dollar amount stated in the adopted, good-faith budget of the timeshare program and (ii)
23 the developer will pay any amount by which all common expenses incurred during the guarantee
24 period exceed the total revenues of the timeshare program during the guarantee period."
25 SECTION 2. Article 4 of Chapter 93A of the General Statutes is amended by adding
26 a new section to read:
27 "§ 93A-62.1. Procedure for timeshare trustee foreclosure of assessment liens.
28 (a) This section is intended to provide, as an alternative to judicial foreclosure, a simple
29 and inexpensive method of enforcing payment of assessments, to the knowledge of all persons,
30 and recognize, in authorizing this timeshare trustee foreclosure proceeding, that all persons
31 owning a timeshare know or should know that the assessment lien on their timeshare may be
32 foreclosed and the timeshare sold for failure to pay assessments.
33 (b) A claim of lien complying with the requirements of G.S. 93A-62(d)(3) and subsection
34 (d) of this section must be filed in the office of the clerk of the superior court of the county in
35 which the timeshare is located in the manner provided in this section.
36 (c) No fewer than 15 days prior to filing the claim of lien, the managing entity or the
37 holder of the lien shall mail a statement of the assessment amount due by first-class mail to the
38 owner's address as recorded in the books and records of the timeshare program. If the record
39 owner is a corporation or limited liability company, the statement shall also be sent by first-class
40 mail to the mailing address of the registered agent for the corporation or limited liability
41 company. Notwithstanding any provision of this Chapter to the contrary, there shall be no
42 requirement that notice under this subsection be mailed to an owner's timeshare unit or otherwise
43 posted at the timeshare project. The managing entity or the holder of the lien shall make diligent
44 efforts to ensure that its records contain the unit owner's mailing address.
45 (d) The person signing the claim of lien on behalf of the holder shall attach to and file
46 with the claim of lien a certificate, that has been signed and sworn to or affirmed before a notary
47 public, certifying that notice of the lien was sent to the record owner and those entitled to receive
48 notice, pursuant to both of the following methods: (i) by registered or certified mail, return receipt
49 requested, or by designated delivery service pursuant to 26 U.S.C. § 7502(f)(2) with a delivery
50 receipt requested and (ii) by mailing a copy of the lien by regular, first-class mail, postage prepaid
Page 4 House Bill 992-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 to the owner's known address as recorded in the books and records of the timeshare program. As
2 used in this section, "delivery receipt" includes an electronic or facsimile receipt.
3 (e) The managing entity, holder of the lien, or designated trustee filing the certificate
4 provided for in subsection (h) of this section shall, at least 30 days prior to docketing the
5 judgment, send notice of the assessment lien foreclosure to the owner in the same manner as a
6 claim of lien under subsection (d) of this section to the owner at the owner's known address as
7 recorded in the books and records of the timeshare program and to all lienholders with liens that
8 have attached after the effective date of the timeshare claim of lien filed in accordance with
9 subsection (b) of this section. The notice required by this subsection shall (i) state that a judgment
10 will be docketed and the proposed date of the docketing, (ii) state that the judgment will authorize
11 a sale of the timeshare pursuant to a timeshare trustee foreclosure proceeding, (iii) provide a brief
12 description of the timeshare affected, (iv) include the filing information for the claim of lien if
13 previously filed with the clerk of the superior court, and (v) state that the lien may be satisfied
14 prior to judgment being entered. The notice shall also include an objection form that the owner
15 can use to object to use of the timeshare trustee foreclosure process within 30 days of receipt of
16 the notice by signing and returning the objection form to the managing entity, holder of the lien,
17 or designated trustee, and in such event the lien may thereafter only be foreclosed by filing a
18 judicial foreclosure action. The objection form described in this subsection shall identify the
19 owner, the timeshare interest, and the return address of the trustee and shall state: "The
20 undersigned owner exercises the owner's right to object to the use of the timeshare trustee
21 foreclosure procedure contained in G.S. 93A-62.1." The notice required by this subsection may
22 be combined with the notice of lien required to be given pursuant to subsection (d) of this section
23 and shall also contain a statement in substantially the following form:
24 "You may choose to sign and send to the trustee the enclosed objection form, exercising your
25 right to object to the use of the timeshare trustee foreclosure procedure. Upon the trustee's receipt
26 of your signed objection form, the foreclosure of the lien with respect to the default specified in
27 this notice shall be subject to the judicial foreclosure procedure only. If you do not object to the
28 use of the timeshare trustee foreclosure procedure, you will not be subject to a deficiency
29 judgment, even if the proceeds from the sale of your timeshare interest are insufficient to offset
30 the amounts secured by the lien."
31 (f) If, within 10 days following the mailing of the notice required by subsection (e) of
32 this section, a return receipt or delivery receipt has not been received by the managing entity,
33 holder of the lien, or designated trustee indicating receipt of the notice, then the managing entity,
34 holder of the lien, or designated trustee shall have a notice published in a newspaper of general
35 circulation in the county where the timeshare is located once a week for two consecutive weeks
36 directed to, and naming, all unnotified lienholders and the owner that a judgment will be docketed
37 against the owner.
38 (g) All costs of mailing and publication, plus a charge of two hundred fifty dollars
39 ($250.00) to defray administrative costs, shall be added to the amount of assessments that are a
40 lien on the timeshare and shall be paid by the owner to the managing entity or holder of the lien
41 at the time the assessments are collected or the timeshare is sold.
42 (h) Except as provided in subsection (s) of this section, no sooner than six months since
43 the indebtedness described in the claim of lien became due and after filing the claim of lien, the
44 managing entity, holder of the lien, or designated trustee may foreclose the lien by filing a
45 certificate, that has been signed and sworn to or affirmed before a notary public, with the clerk
46 of the superior court, showing the following: (i) the record owner of the timeshare on which there
47 is a lien for unpaid assessments, together with the amount of assessments, including taxes,
48 penalties, interest, and costs that are covered by the lien, (ii) the year or years for which the
49 assessments are due, (iii) a description of the timeshare sufficient to permit its identification by
50 parol testimony, and (iv) the filing information for the claim of lien if previously filed with the
51 clerk of the superior court. The fees for docketing and indexing of the certificate assessed
